Zero-knowledge proofs are cryptographic techniques that allow one party (a prover) to prove to another (a verifier) that a statement about some private information is true without revealing one’s identity or the information itself. This has huge advantages:

  • Transactions hide all information about the offline computations.
  • Transactions can be validated in constant time by anyone, regardless of the offline computation.
  • Transactions in Aleo are 968 bytes regardless of the offline computation, and generating them takes less than a minute.
  • Transactions do not use ‘gas’ and so applications have unlimited runtime.
  • Private decentralized exchanges for user-defined fungible assets and regulation-friendly private stablecoins are made possible.

All of this comes together with Aleo’s Consensus Algorithm: Proof of Succinct Work (PoSW).
Zero-knowledge Proofs are all about Privacy

With Web2, we give up privacy to the companies with which we interact. Data leaks, private data monetization, and the permanency of availability of leaked data are all major drawbacks of the Web2 world.

Web3 envisions an open, trustless, permissionless internet where users can interact with each other peer-to-peer without giving up ownership control, privacy, or relying on intermediaries. Aleo offers one of the most important infrastructures of Web3’s future with its zero-knowledge proof — using ZKPs to achieve both privacy and programmability, allowing third parties to verify the truth of your information without needing to reveal it directly.

Say we wanted to create an NFT collection, where each person could only own at most one NFT from the collection. In Web2, doing this would require users to disclose their identities and their NFTs. However, with ZKPs, in Web3, users can reveal proofs of the uniqueness of their identity, without revealing who they are specifically, protecting their full privacy, with all the same guarantees. In a simple transaction example, imagine paying anonymously with your credit card without revealing your name and purchase history.

In the long run, Aleo aims to introduce privacy functionality to many of our daily use cases, such as bank accounts, online shopping, identity verification, social networking, and business, creating a much more private and secure world where everyone gets to own and protect their own data.
Why is Aleo’s Zero-Knowledge Proof Important to Web3?

Token price is affected by dynamic market conditions. Typically the mainet launch happens simultaneously as listing on an exchange which is when the token experiences price discovery, possibly surging exponentially. To put it simply, the earlier you can mine, the more tokens you earn. And on top of that, you can sell your tokens at a higher price when the token is listed on exchanges, resulting in a better ROI.

Participating in first-batch mining is only possible if you’re a professional miner or an experienced mining pool. Procyon is the premiere platform that aims to make first-batch mining accessible to general investors, delivering exceptional ROI.

Shoot for the stars with Procyon.

What Is First-Batch Mining?

First-batch mining begins as soon as the mainnet goes live. This is possible because the first-batch of miners has already acquired hash power through the testnet prior to the launch of the mainnet. Once mainnet goes live, these miners are the first to begin the mining process, achieving much greater ROI while the mining difficulty is low and the mining output is high.

There are two core factors that affect a miner's ROI:

  • 1. Mining output
  • 2. Token price

Mining output is directly related to the mining difficulty. The more miners, the greater the total network-wide hash power, the higher the mining difficulty, and the lower the mining output per miner. The total mineable supply is fixed, so the more hash power that flows into mining, the less mining output is released per unit (TB) of hash power. The output of first-batch mining is usually much greater in comparison to regular mining. You can think of it like sharing a pizza. The more people share, the smaller each slice gets. For example, with Chia mining, the daily output during first-batch mining was equivalent to 1 year of mining at the rates just 2 months after mainnet launch.

Spacemesh & Spacemesh Mining

What is Spacemesh?

Spacemesh is an open-source programmable cryptocurrency platform powered by a novel proof-of-space-time (PoST) consensus protocol. Spacemesh does not use proof-of-stake (PoS) or proof-of-work (PoW) protocols, thus it avoids some of their inherent issues, such as massive energy waste and centralization of mining power.

Spacemesh is designed to achieve three main objectives:

  • Create and maintain the ledger for the Spacemesh coin (SMH). Spacemesh is a fair cryptocurrency and a global means of payment.
  • Ensure fair, wide distribution of SMH.
  • Establish a global programmable infrastructure for tokenized apps, communities and economies.

Who is building Spacemesh?

Spacemesh was created by a top-class team of leaders and developers with decades of experience in startups, blockchain, and venture captial investing.

The co-founders, Tomer Afek and Aviv Eyal, have founded numerous startup ventures which went on to be acquired by the likes of Sony and Taboola.

Who is backing Spacemesh?

In September 2018, Spacemesh concluded a massive $18.5 million investment round led by Polychain Capital, with another round raising $4 million, bringing the total fundraising amount to over $22.5 million.

Other notable Spacemesh backer, Paradigm capital, has previously invested in hugely successful startups and large organizations, such as Uniswap, Coinbase, and Amber Group (leading crypto asset management firm).

Since 2012, Coinbase Ventures, a VC arm under Coinbase, and as of March 2021 is considered the largest exchange in the U.S by trading volume and 3rd largest worldwide.

Furthermore, in an unprecedented announcement on June 12th, 2020, Japanese mobile game and venture capital giant gumi Inc., through its blockchain-focused subsidiary gumi Cryptos Capital, unveiled their partnership with Spacemesh’s parent company, Unruly Technologies Ltd., to assist with market entry in Japan.

When will the Spacemesh network officially launch?

At the moment, the Spacemesh mainnet launch is scheduled for early 2022, but no specific date has been decided as of yet. We will notify all registered users of any updates regarding the Spacemesh mainnet launch as soon as new information becomes available.

Mining & General Cryptocurrency Information

What is mining?

'Mining' is the term used to describe how cryptocurrencies are produced. In order to "mine" a cryptocurrency, computers must solve complex mathematicl equations and if successful, the operators of the computers (also known as mining machines) are given cryptocurrency as a reward.

Much like mining for gold, it takes effort to procure (in the case of cryptocurrencies, computing power or hard disk space), there is a finite supply, and the more that is mined, or the more people attempt to mine it at the same time, the more difficult it is to mine more (this is known as Mining Difficulty, explained below).

What is a mining pool?

A 'mining pool' is a large-scale cryptocurrency mining operation that combines a large number of mining machines together to increase their probability of finding a 'block' on the blockchain and thus gaining cryptocurrencies as a reward (explained below).

What is a Block?

A block is like a page in a bank transaction ledger, which records all past and present transactions on a blockchain and can not be changed. Computers around the world are constantly recording these transactions, and when a block is completed, rewards are given out as an incentive for miners to continue validating the blockchain.

The more computing power you have, the greater your chances of gaining block rewards become.

What is Mining Difficulty?

Mining Difficulty refers to the rate at which cryptocurrencies can be mined. Much like mining for gold in the real world, the more miners, the greater the total network-wide hash power, the higher the mining difficulty, and the lower the mining output per miner. The total mineable supply is fixed, so the more hash power that flows into mining, the less mining output is released per unit (TB) of hash power. The mining output of the first-batch mining is usually much greater in comparison to regular mining as a result.

What is a cryptocurrency wallet? What is a cold wallet? What is the difference?

A cryptocurrency 'wallet' is where your digital currencies are kept, much in the same way you keep fiat currency cash in your wallet in your pocket. Normal online wallets, known as 'hot' wallets, store your cryptocurrencies online. 'Cold' wallets, or hardware wallets, are physical devices that store your cryptocurrencies offline. Though more secure than online 'hot' wallets, if a 'cold' wallet is damaged or lost, the digital assets inside are lost forever.

  • Ensure the token maintains meaningful value
  • Incentivize all participants to contribute to network security
  • Prevent incentives from leading to dishonest behavior
  • Build an ecosystem of useful applications
  • Foster decentralization

To that end, Aleo plans to start mining rewards at 100 Aleo credits per block, which they estimate would result in about 160 million Aleo mined per year, for the first 3 years. As shown in the chart above, the rewards will halve in the fourth year, then again in the seventh year, and they will halve for the final time in the tenth year of the blockchain’s existence.

Along with an initial supply of 1 billion Aleo generated at the start of the blockchain, this would mean that the supply should level off around 2 billion Aleo. Although this means there is no hard cap on the Aleo supply, the ‘tail emissions’ beyond the first decade are a healthy small amount of token inflation, according to the Aleo team.

For first-batch miners this means that in the first 3 years Aleo mining will generate the most rewards. Combined with the common trend that new tokens tend to start at a high valuation and gradually decline, first-batch mining should prove to be most rewarding.

Aleo is the first platform to offer fully private applications. Aleo achieves privacy by leveraging decentralized systems and zero-knowledge cryptography to protect user data on the web.

Using zero-knowledge cryptography, Aleo moves smart contract execution off-chain to enable a diverse range of decentralized applications that are both entirely private and can scale to tens of thousands of transactions per second. Built on an open, public blockchain; Aleo brings all the flexibility of Ethereum but with a more scalable architecture in which miners don’t need to re-run every transaction, but simply verify their correctness.
